media$description.$t:
Asus ZenFone 4 - Hands On - CES 2014

TechnoBufallo CES 2014 hub: http://tchno.be/JDRBP2

We're here at the 2014 Consumer Electronics Show and just spent some time checking out Asus' new family of smartphones, including the new ZenFone 4, ZenFone 5 and ZenFone 6. What we found really surprised us.

You see, we weren't really expecting that much from a handset that commands $99 unlocked. But it's actually a really impressive device. The body doesn't feel as rock solid as a premium phone, but then again you're paying just a fraction of the cost. It reminds us a bit of what the Moto G is: a device that's aimed at consumers who don't need everything, but who also won't settle for junk, either. GALLERY/MORE: http://tchno.be/19ZIVfw

title.$t: Asus Transformer Book Duet TD300 - Hands On - CES 2014

media$description.$t:
Asus Transformer Book Duet TD300 - Hands On - CES 2014

TechnoBufallo CES 2014 hub: http://tchno.be/JDRBP2

The Asus Transformer Book Duet TD300 is a product it can do more than a lot of others can. Asus just announced the device during the 2014 Consumer Electronics Show, and it's pretty wild.

For one, you can switch between running Android 4.3 Jelly Bean or Windows 8.1 at the tap of a button. After about 2-3 seconds, the operating system completely switches and you're in a brand new environment. It's pretty amazing, especially considering that the system can run on an Intel Core i3, Intel Core i5 or Intel Core i7 processor (depending on how you configure it). At the lowest end, it's going to set you back only $599, though, which is really pretty amazing considering the functionality you'll get out of it. GALLERY/MORE: http://tchno.be/Kwthic

media$title.$t: Asus Transformer Book Duet TD300 - Hands On - CES 2014

media$description.$t:
Asus ZenFone 6 Hands On - CES 2014

TechnoBufallo CES 2014 hub: http://tchno.be/JDRBP2

We're really excited by what Asus did with its ZenFone smartphones here at CES 2014. They don't offer the best specs on the planet, but each device is also still super compelling that's to solid design, great color choices and decent components. Take the ZenFone 6, for example, our favorite phone of the bunch that will retail for just $199 without a contract.

We had a chance to spend some time with the ZenFone 6 and really loved the huge 6-inch screen — something that's rarely available (if at all) at the $200 price point unlocked. Under the hood, it has an Intel Atom processor and runs Android 4.3, though Asus promises Android 4.4 KitKat is coming at some point. Toss in a 13-megapixel camera, a 2-megapixel front-facing camera, 1GB of RAM and you have a really compelling handset that's going to bring a lot more folks into the phablet arena. GALLERY/MORE: http://tchno.be/1dwtNUv

Asus ZenFone 5 - Hands On - CES 2014

TechnoBufallo CES 2014 hub: http://tchno.be/JDRBP2

There's a huge trend occurring in the mobile space, and it arguably started sometime last year. During the 2014 Consumer Electronics Show, Asus highlighted the trend: lower-cost handsets that aren't cruddy. They're designed, in most cases, for emerging markets and for folks who don't want to sign a contract but also don't want a handset that packs specs that are a few years old.

Asus' new ZenFone 5 is a perfect example of what's going on. It sports a large 5-inch screen, though without totally first-class specs it's still a 720p screen. Under the hood, it runs Android 4.3 on an Intel Atom processor, but also includes 1GB of RAM an 8-megapixel camera and a 2-megapixel front-facing camera. It also feels pretty solid, and doesn't look cheap at all. For $149, it's definitely something we're looking forward to spending a lot more time with. GALLERY/MORE: http://tchno.be/1lPSMGP

title.$t: Antimicrobial Gorilla Glass First Look - CES 2014

media$description.$t:
Antimicrobial Gorilla Glass - CES 2014

TechnoBufallo CES 2014 hub: http://tchno.be/JDRBP2

Phones are disgusting. Worse, even, than some surfaces you would think are dirtier, like a bathroom stall, or a Las Vegas slot machine. They pick up everything we've touched throughout the day, making them a breeding ground for some not so nice bacteria. Corning is hoping to reduce the amount of bacteria your smartphone collects by actually baking in new antimicrobial technology into its Gorilla Glass. Hopefully that means your smartphone will no longer be a disgusting sewer. MORE: http://tchno.be/Kyeq6P

Parrot this week brought on some reinforcements to its Drone lineup, introducing a new Jumping Sumo and MiniDrone for you to play with. TechnoBufallo CES 2014 hub: http://tchno.be/JDRBP2

Sony and T-Mobile just announced the brand new Xperia Z1s yesterday, an exclusive version of the Xperia Z1 that will only be available on T-Mobile. We had a chance to not only go hands-on with the unit, but also to unbox a unique version that was sent to us here at CES 2014. GALLERY/MORE: http://tchno.be/1a9pA8F

Toshiba Chromebook Hands On - CES 2014

TechnoBufallo CES 2014 hub: http://tchno.be/JDRBP2

Toshiba came to the 2014 Consumer Electronics Show with several new products in tow, but the one that most caught our eye was its Chromebook - the first such device to sport a 13.3-inch display. All things considered, it's a relatively no-frills device, but that's the point of Chromebooks. You get a fully functional laptop with a fully sized keyboard and access to most of Google's services at a very low cost. GALLERY/MORE: http://tchno.be/1fdEPVC

title.$t: Sony Xperia Z1 Compact Hands On - CES 2014

media$description.$t:
Sony Xperia Z1 Compact Hands On - CES 2014

TechnoBufallo CES 2014 hub: http://tchno.be/JDRBP2

We were certain Sony was through announcing new products at its press conference on Monday, but it surprised everybody by introducing the Xperia Z1 Compact, which is essentially a smaller version of the company's famous Z1 flagship. Sony was adamant this is a no-compromise device, just in a smaller package, and our short experience with the handset left us feeling quite impressed by its capabilities. Not only did it feel quick and smooth, but the build quality was incredibly solid; fans of smaller devices will love the Z1 Compact, because it's not simply one of those "mini" iterations other companies have churned out. GALLERY/MORE: http://tchno.be/KyigNj

title.$t: Samsung Galaxy Camera 2 Hands On - CES 2014

media$description.$t:
Samsung Galaxy Camera 2 Hands On - CES 2014

TechnoBufallo CES 2014 hub: http://tchno.be/JDRBP2

Samsung's first Galaxy Camera was a neat experience, one that showed a lot of potential in a point-and-shoot market that was struggling to compete with the growing popularity of smartphones. The integration of Android in a dedicated shooter was near-perfect; unfortunately, the camera only produced mediocre quality, not to mention it was priced fairly high compared to other point-and-shoots. Samsung's brand new Galaxy Camera 2 is meant to address every problem users had with the first iteration, with a stronger build, better internals, and even better software. We played with it at CES on Monday, and immediately fell in love. GALLERY/MORE: http://tchno.be/1cBR5eb

TechnoBufallo CES 2014 hub: http://tchno.be/JDRBP2

Fugoo is a new entry into the wireless speaker market, with Bluetooth 4.0 on board and an interchangeable, chameleon-esque form factor they call "Core + Jacket." Roku TV First Look - CES 2014

TechnoBufallo CES 2014 hub: ‪http://tchno.be/JDRBP2‬

Roku, best known for its set-top boxes, has entered into the world of adding its interface to televisions manufactured by various companies, making the first all-in-one Roku experience.

The new Roku TV sets will be release from both Hisense and TCL this year, but the company assured us while speaking with them at CES 2014 that more companies were already in negotiations to add the interface in the near future. GALLERY/MORE: http://tchno.be/1ePd8xL

title.$t: LG 34-inch UltraWide QHD Monitor First Look - CES 2014

media$description.$t:
LG 34-inch UltraWide QHD Monitor First Look - CES 2014

TechnoBufallo CES 2014 hub: ‪http://tchno.be/JDRBP2‬

Many workflows today rely on a two monitor setup, allowing folks to separate applications for maximum productivity. But looking back and forth between two monitors can be exhausting, and that's assuming you even have space for two large monitors in the first place, which not everyone does. LG has a pretty sweet alternative that we'd have in our office right now if we could. We've actually been using one of LG's UltraWide monitors for the past month, and actually like it quite a bit; it certainly takes some getting used to because of its aspect ratio, but it's a joy to use. Looking at the "world's first" 34-inch UltraWide QHD Monitor from LG, our eyeballs can die happy. GALLERY/MORE: http://tchno.be/1cflagm

title.$t: Sony PlayStation Now First Look - CES 2014

media$description.$t:
Sony PlayStation Now First Look - CES 2014

TechnoBufallo CES 2014 hub: ‪http://tchno.be/JDRBP2‬

Sony's new PlayStation Now streaming service, announced at CES this week, is how Sony wants you to play PlayStation 3 games in the future—and that's just the beginning.

Initially, the company says the service, which is launching in beta later this month and becoming available sometime over the summer, will allow users to play (currently just) PlayStation 3 games over the PlayStation 4, PS Vita, Sony Bravia TVs, and eventually phones and tablets—not just Sony phones, either. It's an ambitious project that's made possible thanks to the company's acquisition of Gakai. MORE: http://tchno.be/1iJhXet

A meeting of two YouTube giants as Jon Rettinger interviews Philip DeFranco high above the floor at CES 2014 in Las Vegas.

Jon and Phil discuss their favorite items on the floor at CES, the future of drones and DeFranco's impending fatherhood. It's a lot of laughs in addition to a whole lot of technology talk. MORE: http://tchno.be/1dk2roc

Toyota FCV Concept Overview - CES 2014

TechnoBufallo CES 2014 hub: ‪http://tchno.be/JDRBP2‬

Toyota's FCV, Fun Candy Vehicle according to Jon or officially Fuel Cell Vehicle according to Toyota, is a mastery of design and science. The Toyota FCV is essentially an electric car that never needs plugging in. It uses hydrogen fuel and  runs for over 300 miles with a full tank. At this point the FCV is just a concept car by all means, but you could see them on the roads as soon as 2015. MORE: http://tchno.be/1eAx1Z9

TechnoBufallo CES 2014 hub: ‪http://tchno.be/JDRBP2‬

CES is where all the big names in tech gather each January to see all of the latest gadgets and gizmos, and it is inevitable that will run into one another, and a video camera is never more than a few feet away. So after our Jon Rettinger sat down with Philip DeFranco, Ashley Esqueda sat down with SourceFed's own Trisha Hershberger.

They discuss the things at the show that excited the most, robots and their dreams for 3D printers that can supply them with a never ending stream of bacon. MORE: http://tchno.be/1lWpbP0

title.$t: Nikon DSLR xxArray 3D Modelling Demo - CES 2014

media$description.$t:
Nikon DSLR xxArray 3D Modelling Demo - CES 2014

TechnoBufallo CES 2014 hub: ‪http://tchno.be/JDRBP2‬

Nikon was showing off its new xxArray here at CES 2014, and if you've ever wanted to live in a video game, this may be your chance.

The xxArray features an assortment of 48 Nikon DLSRs arranged at various points around your body to shoot you from every conceivable angle. After two hours of processing time you have a playable version of yourself to put into a video game. The copy may not be perfect - that would require some additional time not to be had on the floor of CES - but who cares when you could b placed in the Halo universe? MORE: http://tchno.be/1j4hfeC

media$description.$t:
UHD TV Overview - CES 2014

TechnoBufallo CES 2014 hub: ‪http://tchno.be/JDRBP2‬

If there was any big buzzword at CES 2014, it had to be "UHD TVs." You could barely walk five feet without seeing a new model, and while 4K has been the big thing for a while, there were already 5K and 8K models already on display at the show. While 5K will be available this year, the 8K models are still a ways off from being available to consumers.

It seemed like every company had something to show off in the form of UHD this year, but what does this mean for the consumer? Jon Rettinger attempts to break it down for you. MORE: http://tchno.be/19qt5MN

Sharp Q+ Televisions Eyes-On (Sponsored)

The 4K television revolution is upon us, but what if you don't want to go quite that far yet in your purchase of a new TV set? What if you would prefer something that could handle 4K content, but not break the bank? Sharp has the answer for you with its new line of Q+ sets. http://tchno.be/19sEgEM

Besides seeing all of the products companies have coming out for the year, the majority of them also like to give you a peak at some of the trands you could see over the next few years. Sharp had several such televisions on display, and they made us wish the future was now.

Have you ever wished your television had no visible borders to the screen? Sharp is working on that. Ever dreamed of an 8k 3D TV that doesn't require glasses? The company had one of those on display as well.

Sharp is pushing the television set industry forward, and we're glad we're able to be along for the ride.
